@Node Mappers " Mappers "

	Mappers
	=======
	NES games uses special hardware (="mappers") to
	work around memory limitations for both code and graphics.
	Those mappers differs alot in complexity. The simplest
	ones are (partly) emulated in A/NES PRO, and others (usually
	more complex) are not emulated.
	
	If you can read a "(!)" close to the mappernumber in the
	GUI, this is the way A/NES PRO tells you that this mapper
	is not implemented.
	Running a NES game with a unsupported mapper may result
	in strange behaviour or game crashes.

	However, if you do not see this sign and the game still
	behaves weird, it is a possibility that the mapper
	is not fully(correctly) emulated.



@Endnode
@Node GFX " Graphics "

	Graphicsdrivers
	===============
	A/NES PRO v1.10 has support for two gfxdrivers.

	ECS/AGA  = Use this if you only have ECS or AGA chipset.
	CGFX/P96 = If you have got a graphicscard, you can try this
		   mode.
	NatAmi   = Not yet available.

	
	The CGFX/P96 mode is at the moment work-in-progress and
	is not yet perfect, so use with care.
	To be able to use this mode you must pick a suitable
	256x240x8 screenmode (check the preferences-section). 
	This screenmode MUST be a graphicscard screenmode (with "chunky"
	graphics).

	Notice, the CGFX/P96 mode does not multitask at the
	moment.



@Endnode
@Node Important " Important "


	Important
	=========
	A/NES PRO detects which region the game was designed for and
	sets the correct screenmode(PAL/NTSC) while emulating.
	It is important that the header of the NES roms are correct to
	get proper emulation.
	90% of all ROMs floating around are NTSC which means you
	probably doesnt need to bother. However, a few are PAL and
	might not have a correct header set and this will most
	likely result in degraded emulation.
	If you are familiar with hex-editors, verify bit 0 of byte 9
	in the header, it should be set to "1" of the game is PAL.
	
	If A/NES PRO does not find any regioninformation in the header,
	the filename is analyzed. If there is a "(E)" found, the game
	is treated as PAL, otherwise NTSC.


@Endnode
@Node SHELL " Commandline/Tooltypes "

	Icon/Tooltype
	=============
	Create an icon (project-type) for your .NES-ROM. Set
	"anespro" as default-tool and make sure your A/NES PRO
	installation is in your current path.
	Now you can start your NES-ROMs from an icon, just like
	they were normal Amiga-games!


	Commandline
	===========
	A/NES PRO can be used with commandline parameters now.
	Usage is pretty simple:
	1>anes dh2:SuperMarioBros.nes
        or
        1>anes "dh2:Legend of zelda.nes"

	No GUI is visible when starting A/NES PRO this way. 
	However, emulation settings is still read from the 
	S:ANESPRO.prefs file (created by A/NES PRO when saving
	the settings).


@Endnode
@Node SaveState " Savestate "

	Savestate
	=========
	-- Savestate temporarily disabled. -- 


	A/NES PRO has a built-in savestate feature. By pressing F5
	during gameplay the current state will be freezed and with
	F6 you'll restore this state.
	Could be usefull to save the state before you try to
	beat that ugly boss. If you fail, just reload the state
	and try again. :-)

	Please notice that savestate feature is still experimental
	and may not work properly with all games/mappers.
	

@Endnode

@Node FDS " FDS Emulation "

	FDS emulation
	=============
	A/NES PRO now has partial FDS emulation. FDS images are
	diskimages of 3" disks that were available for the
	japanese Famicom in the 80's.

	Requirements
	------------
	To emulate FDS, you need to have a copy of the FDS
	BIOS located in your S: directory. The file should
	be called "disksys.rom". If this file isn't present,
	emulation would not work.


	How to change disk/swap side
	----------------------------
	* Start emulation, when the BIOS prompts to insert a disk,
	press HELP-key (=insert disk)
	* If the game prompts to you change disk side. The procedure
	is as follows:
		1) Eject disk (press "DEL")
		2) Press "1"(Side A) or "2"(Side B) for which side to
		   insert.
		3) Insert the disc (press "HELP")
		4) The game will hopefully continue to load.


	Limitations
	===========
	* Saving to FDS disk is not yet supported.
	* FDS additional soundchannels are not emulated.


@Endnode

@Node tech " -÷×÷- A/NES -÷×÷- "


        @{b}TECHNICAL INFORMATION@{ub}

        The following utilities was used during the
        development of A/NES.

                * ASM-ONE / ASM-PRO
                * GADTOOLSBOX

        A/NES consists of more than 17.000 lines of 
        pure assembly code. The source code (including gui)
        is about 375 Kbyte in size.

        The 6502 cpu emulation is NOT based on any existing
        source and is written from scratch in assembly, making
        special use of the 68020 processor or better.


@Endnode

@Node Prefs " -÷×÷- A/NES - GUI & Preferences -÷×÷- "


        @{b}GUI@{ub}
        Explaning about @{b}Load / Start ROM@{ub} is not needed I guess. :)
        The "continue" button will let you continue your game
        when you have aborted it (by for example pressing the escape-key).
        However this button is not entirely reliable yet so use
        it with care.



        @{b}PREFERENCES@{ub}

        Features enabled at this time are:

        @{" GENERAL " Link GenPrefs} @{" EMULATION " Link EmuPrefs} @{" CHEAT " Link CheatPrefs}



        --------------------------------------------------------





@Endnode

@Node GenPrefs " -÷×÷- A/NES -÷×÷- "


        @{b}GENERAL WINDOW@{ub}


        @{b}LIMIT SPEED@{ub}
	Limits the game to 50/60fps (depending if the ROM is NTSC or PAL).
	If you have got a very fast CPU, you might need this option.
        Default = checked


        @{b}AUTOSAVE BATTERY@{ub}
        Turn this function off if you don't want to save the
        battery.
        Default = checked

        @{b}USE BATTERY PATH@{ub}
        As default, all battery files (.sav) will be saved
        in the same directory as the .NES file. But when this
        box is checked you can have your battery files in
        a different directory. Remember to set your default
        battery-path by pressing the @{b}Battery@{ub}-button.


        @{b}AUTOSAVE PREFS@{ub}
        When this function is on, preferences-settings will be
        saved when you quit A/NES. If turned off, no settings
        will be automatically saved.

        @{b}IGNORE LED@{ub}
        Here is a real usefull option! :D
        When this button is cleared, A/NES automatically
        takes care of switching on/off the hardware sound-
        filter to improve sound quality.
        Check this if you don't want A/NES to do that.
        Default = cleared

        @{b}USE COMMENT AS TITLE@{ub}
        When this function is active, the game title will be
        grabbed from the file-comment instead of the game itself.
        Could be usefull for XPK-packed ROMs.


        @{b}JOYPAD 1@{ub}
        Selects if you want to use keyboard/CD32 pad for
        emulating joypad 1. Support for more pads will be
        added later.


        @{b}JOYPAD 2@{ub}
        Selects between "Disable" or "CD32". You should choose
        "disable" if you don't want to use joypad2 (will
        save a few cycles) or if you haven't got a CD32
        compatible joypad. :) 


       

@Endnode

@Node EmuPrefs " -÷×÷- A/NES PRO -÷×÷- "


        @{b}EMULATION WINDOW@{ub}


        @{b}Ignore bad opcodes?@{ub}
        Some ROMs floating around contain flaws (Adventure of
        Lolo 1). Check this option if you don't want A/NES PRO to
        quit emulation when executing a bad opcode.


        @{b}EMULATE SOUND@{ub}
        Turn sound emulation on / off. Saves a few cycles
        but shouldn't be noticable.

        @{b}TRACKDISK EMULATION@{ub}
	If you miss the sound from an FDS diskdrive reading FDS
	games during play, this option is for you.
	This option simulates the audio caused by the FDS during
	reading the disk. Please notice that you need to have
	an AmigaDOS floppy into drive DF0: when using this option.
	Any floppydisk would do as long it's an Amiga formatted
	disk.
	Only dummy-data is read from this floppy and no writing
	is ever done (however, keep the disk write-protected just
	in case :))
	
        @{b}FRAMESKIP@{ub}
	Check this option to make A/NES PRO skip every second
	frame to speed of the emulation. Makes emulation faster
	but graphics looks worse.

        @{b}MODE@{ub}
        Select which graphicsdriver you want to use. You have
        three to choose from:
        ECS/AGA , CGFX/P96 and NatAmi.
	Natami-driver is not available at the moment.


        @{b}Screenmode@{ub} (CGFX/P96 only)
        Picks a screenmode for use with the CGFX/P96-driver.
        Must be a 8-bit screen and atleast 256x240 in size.



@Endnode
@Node CheatPrefs " -÷×÷- A/NES PRO -÷×÷- "


        @{b}CHEAT WINDOW@{ub}

        @{" ACTION REPLAY INFORMATION " Link codes}

        If you look on the left side of this window, you will
        discover several "string gadgets", they look something
        like this:


        action replay 
        .------------. .------------.   .------------. .------------.
        |            | |            |   |            | |            |
        `------------' `------------'   `------------' `------------'

        game genie 

        .------------. .------------.   .------------. .------------.
        |            | |            |   |            | |            |
        `------------' `------------'   `------------' `------------'

        In the Action Replay gadgets you can input Action Replay
        codes (really!) :)
        You can have four different codes activated at once.

        Game Genie codes works just like the ActionReplay codes.
        These codes will also be saved along with your saved patch
        files.

        @{b}Note@{ub} that all values you type are default as HEX code, which
        means you don't have to type $-signs or similar. Valid
        characters are 0-F, any other characters will be ignored.
        Also, be sure to "fill" the entire "string-fields", for example
        if you want to "poke" at adress 10, be sure to write 010!


        @{b}Cheat description@{ub} - here you type a 64 character
        long description of your cheat. This is only usefull if you
        want to save your cheat into a special patch (.pat) file,
        so you don't have to type your cheatcodes more than once.

        @{b}Activate@{ub} - Be sure this button is activated if you
        want to use the current cheat codes.

        @{b}Save@{ub} - Press this and your current cheat will be
        saved as a file.

        @{b}Load@{ub} - Loads a cheatfile.

        
        @{b}Get filepath@{ub} - Press this button to select a suitable 
        path for storing your cheatfiles.
        There seems to be some kind of bug left in this code since
        the ROM path & cheat files path are mixed sometimes. Nothing
        serious though...
        


@Endnode
@Node New " -÷×÷- A/NES What's new? -÷×÷- "

        @{b}Features@{ub}

        - Full 6502 emulation (incl. ALL timings!)
        - Battery backup
        - Nice looking gui! :)
        - Action Replay/Game Genie code support!
        - Sound support
	- FDS emulation!
        - Splitscreen scrolling
        - Two player support
        - Vs.Unisystem support
        - CD32 joypad support
        - XPK support
        - Supports the most common mappers (more or less).
	- Supports Famicom Disk System games!
        - Written in 100% 680x0 assembler code

        Note! A/NES PRO only supports loading of XPK packed ROM
        files, not battery save files (*.sav). 


        @{b}Compability@{ub}

	A/NES PRO supports two fileformat. INES (*.nes) and FDS (*.fds).
	To be able to run FDS games, you need to have the Famicom
	Disk System BIOS located in your S: drawer (S:disksys.rom).
	FDS games that saves to disk is not yet supported.


@Endnode
@Node Use " -÷×÷- A/NES PRO Controls -÷×÷- "

	@{b}FDS@{ub}
	----------
	When running an FDS game, a few special keys are
	required.
	
	DEL	    - Ejects the inserted disk
	HELP	    - Insert disk
	1	    - Set Side A
	2	    - Set Side B


	@{b}JOYSTICK 1@{ub}
	----------

        When selecting "keyboard" in the preferences window,
        the following keys will work:

	ENTER       - Start
	RIGHT SHIFT - Select
	LEFT AMIGA  - A
	LEFT ALT    - B
        ARROWKEYS   - Guess what? :)
        BACKSPACE   - Insert Coin (VS.Unisystem ROMS only!)
        F10         - Emulates a NES-reset.

        ESCAPE      - Abort emulation


        ... or if you decide to use a CD32 compatible joypad:

        @{b}CD32@{ub}
        ----

        YELLOW      - Start
        GREEN       - Select
        RED         - A
        BLUE        - B
        PAUSE       - Abort emulation


	@{b}JOYSTICK 2@{ub}
	----------
        Choose between "disabled" or "CD32", that suites you
        the best.
        The keyboard is always locked to joystick 1 and may
        not be used by player 2.
        Always set this to "disable" when not using joystick 2.

        Support for more pads will be added in the future.


@Endnode
@Node Bugs " -÷×÷- A/NES PRO Bugs -÷×÷- "

	@{b}Known bugs@{ub}
	* Some mappers are not 100% emulated, may cause gfxbugs.
	* Diskdrive motor is not turned off when exiting FDS
        emulation and trackdisk option is selected.
        * More.. :)

	@{b}Reporting bugs@{ub}

	Audio aswell works better in some games than others. The
	Amiga only has 4 channels of audio and the NES has 5 that
	somewhat limits the audioquality aswell.

	If your bugs fits the above description, you don't need to
	e-mail me.

	* 

	However, if you have problems with crashes of A/NES PRO or
	similar wierd behaviour, feel free to e-mail me!
	Don't forget to mention your complete setup, OS-version
	etc etc.



@Endnode
@Node Requirements " -÷×÷- A/NES PRO Requires -÷×÷- "

	@{b}Requirements@{ub}

        - ECS chipset
        - 68020+ (overclocked 68060 highly recommended!)
        - ~4Mb of FASTMEM
        - reqtools.library
        - lowlevel.library (if you want CD32 joypad support!)
        - xpkmaster.library (for loading XPK files!)
	- For FDS-emulation, a copy of the FDS BIOS ("disksys.rom")
	  must be placed in your S: drawer.


	A/NES PRO is designed for high-end classic Amigas and run
	better on fast CPU:s (040/060).
	Running A/NES PRO on slower CPU:s (020/030) is not recommended
	(may change in the future)



@Endnode
@Node Introduction " -÷×÷- A/NES PRO Introduction-÷×÷- "



        @{b}Introduction@{ub}

        It all started a day in may in the year of 1997. I was
        watching Nesticle on a PC machine and started to wonder
        why there wasn't any decent NES emulator for Amiga...
        So I (Morgan) and my friend Fredrik started this little
        project.
        We had never done anything like this before so it was
        a challenge.
        The CPU emulation (it's incredible fast) was written
        from scratch in 68020 assembly language and everything
        else concerning the emulation is also written in assembly.

	****

	The story continues.

	Development stopped for a few years, but now I (Morgan)
	decided to start all over again. A/NES became A/NES PRO
	for high-end classic Amigas.

	A/NES PRO is based on the sourcecode of "classic" A/NES
	but with an entirely new graphicsengine.



@Endnode

@Node Installation " -÷×÷- How 2 A/NES PRO -÷×÷- "


        @{b}Installation@{ub}

	Copy the included folder to your harddrive. 

	1. Copy included fonts/ folder to FONTS:
	2. Copy the A/NES PRO folder to your harddrive.
	3. Done! :)



@Endnode
